    {
        "content": "<p>So does this mean</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">findim</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">Î </span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">K</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u_2</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">field</span> <span class=\"n\">K</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">V</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">add_comm_group</span> <span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">vector_space</span> <span class=\"n\">K</span> <span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">],</span> <span class=\"n\">â„•</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>is a better definition (which should be an invisible change to uses of findim without an <code>@</code>).<br>\nIs this something we should be changing everywhere then?<br>\nI guess we could make a linter for this: Like non-instance binders must come as late as possible in the list of binders?</p>",
        "id": 221632158,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1609843307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not the literal order that matters, but the dependencies.  As long as there are type-class arguments that depend on <code>V</code>, you can't rewrite <code>V</code>.</p>",
